text: I go and see this movie last night after be coax to by a few friend of mine I will admit that I be reluctant to see it because from what I know of Ashton Kutcher he be only able to do comedy I be wrong Kutcher play the character of Jake Fischer very well and Kevin Costner play Ben Randall with such professionalism the sign of a good movie be that it can toy with our emotion this one do exactly that the entire theater which be sell out be overcome by laughter during the first half of the movie and be move to tear during the second half while exit the theater I not only see many woman in tear but many full grown man as well try desperately not to let anyone see they cry this movie be great and I suggest that you go see it before you judge

for a moment let us put aside the cultural aspect of this movie even if it be a very important side of it and let us look at the simple fact that this be a very nice love story two individual find themselves in a difficult situation cause by two selfish husband they have to live through their sad day without any ray of hope if each one of these two woman have be alone imagine what kind of life each one would have have to accept they find each other and they fall in love that this love be against all the social religious and cultural law of their environment be almost irrelevant they love each other find relief in each other that be sufficient the reaction of the individual around they be but a small fact that they have to accept suffer even and then they can go on with their life their life very nice

as well as be a portrayal of a lesbian love story FIRE be also a comic satire of middle class indian culture I find this be a quality which be little appreciated about the movie these two genre ie deep meaningful alternative love story and comic satire usually mix together just as well as oil and water do but Mehta somehow manage to achieve the balance to near perfection the servant Jatin s behaviour the family s treatment of he the bedridden grandmother be constant inescapable presence Ashok s obsession with a swami s teaching come from a culture much like India s these be thing I can immediately identify as be typical they have be cry out to be point out and ridicule while develop her primary subject matter Mehta manage to achieve this secondary theme skillfully in fact much of the humour in the film which provide essential relief from the heavy subject of taboo lesbian love and gender issue stem from this satire of the seemingly ordinary the film flow from the comic to the serious with great subteltybr br all in all brilliant use of symbolic device Radha compare to Sita of legend and come out of Fire unscathed and therefore pure the lifelong desire of the young Radha to see the ocean finally achieve when she gain freedom kudo to Shabana azmiradha the lighting crew and Deepa Mehta their very un Hollywood like and un bollywood like talent make this movie special one criticism the first scene seem rather disjointed to I in that they do not flow into each other very wellbr br The verdict 9 on 10 nothing less for a movie with scene so burn on my mind

easily one of the good indian film ever grant that be not say muchI make this conclusion after a whopping 15 minute of watching but I can truly say that Fire be also one of the really beautiful and brilliant film I have seenbr br beautiful because of its imagery the good example I can give be the parallelism between the 2 female leadsradha and Sita and the character of the same name in Hindu mythology Sita for example be the wife of the revere Lord Ram as legend go Ram subjugate his wife by make she walk through a Fire to prove her purity Sita in response cry and leave he reunite with she motherthe Earth this story have all sort of crazy link to the story of the 2 indian womennandita Das and Shabana Azmi the word Fire all of a sudden have many meaning marriage tradition religion motherhood and probably a few other I do not catchbr br brilliant because of its social overtone many who be offend by the premise for this movie should in fact be first to see Fireeg my mom who actually love it why because although Fire be an attack on tradition it be also an attack on tradition in other word that be its strength not its weakness traditional conservative social moreswhether indian or canadian or american or whatever be useless if they enslave you gender role and self denial can both do thisbr br these be the thing I take with I after see Fire hat off to Deepa Mehta

the movie be really about choice in the oppress state of affair as see in Fire where good woman have to be obedient and do what be correct in the eye of tradition there seem few option for Radha and Sita however grant that it be not their only option what be life without desire Radha question Ashok yes it be true that life provide we with a number of option but how many we can take depend on a number of external factor when your world be confine to a small indian household be a dutiful daughter in law to a silent but observant still powerful matriarch a dutiful wife of 13 year to a man who have take a vow of celibacy due to your not be able to have a child a man who only want you lie next to he to prove his strength in eliminate his desire I feel the lady have little choice but to find solace in each other s company I guess the fact that so many woman applaud Ms Mehta s work be because it provide they with an option to think for themselves an option to do what be perhaps unacceptable the lesbian scene I feel be merely to put that point across every scene in the movie from the first at the Taj Mahal to the last at the Mosque be etch in my mind how frustrating to be a prisoner of your feeling and desire to feel that you have to forgo the human touch to be a dutiful wife just because it be expect of you to have to suppress any desire you might have and to crave for the human touch what then be the meaning of our existence one wonder in the scene where Sita be cry alone in the room and Radha come in to comfort she their lip accidentally brush against each other and it awaken a feeling in they something they have both be deprive ofbr br Bravo to Ms Mehta in translate her vision so clearly I especially like the flashback to the young Radha try to see for the ocean it be a metaphor for freedom freedom to choose freedom to transport ourselves to place we would normally be unable to reach in those scene it be gently tell to we that her sense of duty have also be pass down from her mother who I assume live within the rich indian tradition of duty in marriage the movie be beautifully film and enhance by the musical score by AR Rahman since the film I have become ardent fan of the two lead actress and the director I look forward to more of Ms Deepa s future production

Deepa Mehta s Fire be groundbreaking bold and artistic a masterful social commentary on the plight of the woman from conservative upper middle class indian household this be a film no one should miss Shabana Azmi and Nandita Das give stellar performance by underplay their character as much as possible AR Rahman s music be the work of the genius and almost play the role of another character in the film Mehta use Rahman s score and together they create such amazing sound montage that effectively portray the view of the world around Radha and Sita whenever they look to each other for support this film be not about lesbianism as many have brand it lesbianism be just a part of the film it be unfortunate that most people tend to write the film off call it taboo instead of give it a chance and look at its real meaning

for all that have be say about the subject matter and the controversy that surround it please do not overlook what I feel to be the most important part of the film the salient struggle of everyone to keep their pride through their trial whether deal with self impose male braggadocio a sexual reawakening or even life itself everybody be human

water 2005 the final part of Toronto base indian film director Deepa Mehta s elemental trilogy have be finally complete almost ten year after the release of the very first controversial element Fire 1996 which be follow with a slightly less controversial sequel 1947 Earth 1998 Mehta make her directorial debut with a 24 minute canadian short film at 99 a portrait of Louise Tandy Murch 1975 but it be her canadian feature film about the life of Indians live in Canada that bring her fame back in east her country by birthright Sam I 1991 Recognition internationally come in the way of Camilla 1994 star Bridget Fonda along with the actress who in 1990 win an Oscar in Best Actress in a leading Role category at the age of 80 pave the way for middle aged actress to still have hope for her portrayal of a stubborn old jewish woman in drive Miss Daisy 1989 late Jessica Tandy br br Camilla deal with a friendship between two woman from two other end of the human lifespan a May December friendship Camilla be Tandy s last picture she die the very same yearbr br international fame follow Deepa Mehta in 1996 with the release of the controversial Fire which spread with rage among the false patriotic consciousness exist indian extremist having already explore friendship between two woman in Camilla in Fire Mehta go a step far to portray a more intimate relationship between two lonely neglect woman Set in modern day India the suburb of the capital city of New Delhi it show two brother and their wife the eld brother Kulbhushan Kharbanda having join a weird Hindu sect lead a life of celibacy faithful to his guru of sexless existence the young brother Javed Jaffrey be have an extra marital affair with a chinese woman Alice Poon thus both the wife Shabana Azmi play the eld brother wife and Nandita Das the young wife find themselves neglect in their own way one force to lead a celibate life thank to her husband s eccentricity and the other whose only interaction with her husband be through sex and nothing more live in a world of in law and be the only two outsider in the family have nobody else to confide in the two woman fall in the arm of each other thus come the issue of lesbianism if there be an outside man s shoulder to cry on there most probably would have be chance for they to fall into the arm of a man but have no one else to confide in their need for each other support be quite obvious it do not necessarily state that all neglect woman would end up take lesbianism it just happen to exist with regard to the two woman in this context all in all the movie be excellent and delve far deeply than just two woman roll in bed the key focus be not lesbianism in the movie but the plight of modern day neglect indian wife even in the capital city the two female character just happen to have a sexual relationship br br Two year later Deepa Mehta s second installment be the element of mother earth release in India by the name of 1947 earthyet another excellent movie by a great director this time in the Hindi language unlike fire which be make in the english language br br Now Deepa Mehta have manage to complete the trilogy despite a lot of problem having release the final installment recently water no doubt it would be just as great as the other two

this be a bold movie to hit indian cinema when it be release the first movie to perhaps openly depict lesbian tendency amongst indian woman the lead actress of indian cinema Shabana Azmi add substance to the movie with her hot passionate scene with Nandita dasbr br The movie ooze with sexuality and the director use sex in the good way possible the sex be not for erotic purpose but be in the context of the movie the scene where Nandita Das lose her virginity to her husband certainly be the first of its kind in Indian cinemasbr br good act by all the actor especially Nandita Das amidst criticism from the indian public

I admire Deepa Mehta and this movie be a masterpiece I would recommend to buy this movie on DVD because it be a movie you might want to watch more often than just once and trust I you would still find little meaningful detail after watch it several timesbr br The character except for the grandmother perhaps be all very balanced no black and white even though you follow the story from the perspective of the two protagonist there be also empathy for the other charactersbr br I think the IMDb rating for the movie be far too low probably due to its politically controversial content

its a very sensitive portrayal of life with unquenched or constrained desire what do one do with desire in a culture and society with rigid norm one husband find outlet with the immigrant since immigrant do not belong or be not accept they do not need to conform and dam their desire the other husband look for solace in spirituality and try to evaporate his desire into nothingness it fail of course and he break down in the last scene for multiple reason Sita still care enough for he to find that moment to let he know that he be not responsible for her deviant outlet to her block desire the mother in she still could not find the strength to destroy his myth she see he as a child who be glorify himself in his lust control but should she give he the opportunity to finally grow up both the wife find courage and togetherness through their share rejection by their husband br br but the final act of rejection be by the grandmother she could not break free from her rust mindset to accept Sita s desire a decade and more of receive care be not enough to break the shackle of her culturebr br Seems like it be easy for the househelp to let his desire flow since he be anyway damn by his culture be at the bottom of the hierarchy since there be anyway no respect and expectation might as well taste sin

it be more a subtle story of the fact that in indian household how most decision be take by the man how no attention be pay to the desire of the lady for example how even when the husband and wife sleep together it would be a test for the husband whether he can control his desire not to give the woman pleasure and in such a type of scenario woman invariably have two choice either to accept all this and take it into their own life which be usually the case or not accept this and try to mould thing to satisfy themselves which make a moviebr br Fire be a brilliantly direct story of the second option which woman choose for themselves no sacrifice not to serve anybody else rather a decision for their own good somehow the whole idea of justify lesbianism do not find an acceptance in the indian audience but if one look the whole movie from an angle of self expression then the whole debate do not even arise

while the romance in this film be an important aspect it be largely about the role of responsibility and duty in modern Indian all of the major character be well fleshed out and have their own inner life I recommend this strongly

one of good movie ever fire it be not much about sociological description of India today it be the mind blow use of light that never stop never become normal even when in this sense the movie be almost unique both lead be of very good quality the origin of Das as a street performer be pretty obvious her performance be a superb cammeo but the use of the light I have look at it and look at it again and again still mind blow after age nothing torrid in the story rather pure way of face the subject in a way it be sad that in the bizarre world we live today a major art work be usually know as a gender film fire can stand face to face with Dryer s Jeanne D Arc or Ichikawa s Biruma no Tategoto or some of the major Kurosawa movie just to name some wish my input could help a little this movie to its deserve way to fame

I finally watch the third film in Mehta s trilogy fire to begin I would say that water be the unquestionable masterpiece on all level Fire come next with Earth close behind in order of quality fire there be so much go on in this film that I will need a few more viewing to drink it all in the writing be superb the script create friction that start the entire process of heat from the beginning until the end when it really do erupt into a fire the conflict move into complete rupture of relationship br br Mehta be one brave lady she see with a clear eye much that be jaundice false and repressive about the great society from which she come from India be rapidly change these day but much of this be economic change that she meet with such ferocious opposition to the making of water after having have the script clear show that there be still many taboo subject which indian people more than less can not look squarely in the face can not examine or discuss they bad if someone like Mehta have the courage to hold up a mirror to these issue she face death threat so as much as India think of itself as a pluralistic tolerant society the fact be not always so whereas earth be merely a historical setting of the carnage of the civil war after indian independence Fire and Water be point at personal social and religious issue which as I say be consider so strongly in a negative sense that an open artistic dialog be still many year away as I write this water be schedule to actually be show in India later this year I will believe it when I see it br br Fire confront a similar sexual and emotional conundrum that I see in a price above ruby whether it be arrange marriage which it use to be like among Jews about 150 year ago or like it be among many modern Indians they have the risk of have a bad match force upon both man and woman or just plain loveless marriage however this be not the real issue Mehta be clearly impatient with the totally rigid religious attitude that either keep widow in misery water or else keep woman enslave to loveless marriage Fire I be no expert regard either the secular or Hindu law concern divorce the film seem to imply that the stigma of divorceis almost as bad as the sad marriage in any case Mehta s film be a very moving powerful attempt at sexual discourse that hold modern indian relationship up to probe scrutiny that all three of these film have make themselves feel in India as an unwarranted attack on their culture sound to I like the predictable clamor of a repressive mindset Mehta be force the issue to be look at no matter how much flack I admire her work and can not highly recommend her film enough superb disturbing provocative taboo shattering

I be look forward to the Guardian but when I walk into the theater I be not really in the mood for it at that particular time it be kind of like the Olive Garden I like it but I have to be in the right mindset to thoroughly enjoy itbr br Im not exactly sure what be dampen my spirit the trailer look good but the water theme be give I bad flashback to the last Kevin Costner movie that deal with the subject waterworld plus despite the promise Ashton Kutcher show in the Butterfly effect I be still not completely sell on he something about the guy just annoy I probably have to do with his simian featuresbr br it take approximately two minute for my fear to subside and for my hesitancy to slip away the movie immediately throw we into the midst of a tense rescue mission and I be grip tight than Kenny Rogers orange face lift my concern briefly bristle at Kutcher s initial appearance due to the fact that too much effort be make to paint he as ridiculously cool and rebellious sunglass a tough guy toothpick in his mouth and sportin a smirk that would make George Clooney proud yeah we get it I be totally ready to hate himbr br but then he have to go and deliver a fairly strong performance and force I to soften my jab br br Darn you ape man efficiently mix tense exciting rescue scene drama humor and solid acting the Guardian be easily a film that I dare say the majority of audience will enjoy you can quibble about its clichs predictability and rare moment of overcooked sappiness but none of that take away from the entertainment valuebr br I have a bad feeling that the pace would slow too much when Costner start train the young guy but on the contrary the training session just might be the most interesting aspect of the film Coast Guard Rescue Swimmers be hero whose story have never really be portray on the big screen so I feel the inside look at what they go through and how tough it be to make it be very informative and a great way to introduce audience to this under appreciated groupbr br Do you have what it take to be a rescue swimmer just think about it you get to go on dangerous mission in cold dark rough water and then you must fight disorientation exhaustion hypothermia and a lack of oxygen all while try to help strand panic people who be depend on you for their survival and if all that be not bad enough sometimes you can not save everybody so you have to make the tough decision of who live and who diesbr br Man who want all that responsibility not I I have no idea what it be really like for these guy and who would have think I would have an Ashton Kutcher Kevin Costner movie to thank for the education br br Not only do the Guardian do a great job of pay tribute to this rare breed of hero but lucky for we it also do a good job of entertain its pay customersbr br THE GIST br br moviegoer want an inside look at what it be like to embark on a daring rescue mission in the middle of the ocean might want to give the Guardian a chance I see it for free but have I pay I would ve feel I have get my money s worth

there be question that sometimes hover over we and have no answer two woman progressively find themselves ensnare in each other s arm as corny as the expression sound that be exactly what happen and fin that they can not answer their own question as to what define their relationship when their very own society have no name to what they be Deepa Mehta s somewhat mis title FIRE be the first of a loosely connected trilogy here link by the theme of the element and more symbolic than consume fire as uncontrolled erotic passion do not make an appearance here since the woman the old and more feminine Radha Shabana Azmi and the young more masculine temper Sita Nandita Das come to realize they share a lot more than common idea and affection for each other and stand for what they believe be their passion for each other despite the opposition face by their very traditional husband and family as in WATER FIRE be deeply spiritual even if it technically fall into the mode of sentimental melodrama where water much like the weight of the word carry a strong meaning that ultimately transcend its definition even so it be a very beautiful picture and a strong voice from a strong director

now I do understand that this film be not mean as an indictment against all Indians but it be an amazing film because it dare to investigate the hypocrisy that some Indians have concern their woman and sexuality I have know for some time that sexism be very common in this society with woman be murder because the husband s family do not want they any more after his death or because she have a small dowry as well as the frequent killing of female fetus because they be see as a curse instead of a blessing I also realize that some from this culture will be greatly offend by the film but the bottom line be that there be some truth to the subject matter even if the film be so strongly attack when it debut in India a decade ago as a result of the extreme misogyny in the movie most western audience member will be shock or at least be emotionally pull into the plight of the lady in this filmbr br Although I be a male be not rabidly feminist and I be straight the film have a strong positive impact on I and it be not an agenda film that can only be enjoy by Lesbians and man hater in fact I do not think the film be promote hatred of man or homosexuality but instead give a credibly argument how in the case of these two lady it be the only reasonable alternative due to their wicked husband yes I use the word wicked and mean it as both husband live in this large household be intensely selfish and have no regard for their spouse sexuality in many traditional society this be indeed the case and woman be doom to an empty emotional existencebr br One husband marry a vivacious young woman Sita out of family obligation this arranged marriage be uncomfortable for they both but in the beginning Sita make an attempt to connect with her sullen husband however he see himself as a victim and could have care less about Sita and he continue to have an affair with a liberal minded chinese lady to make matter worse he do nothing to hide the affair and make no apology in their dead marriage sex be purely mean to produce child and there be no way Sita could have any of her sexual or emotional need meet and unfortunately he could have care lessbr br Another husband be married to a lady who be infertile Radha oddly after initially try to have child they have go the next 13 year without any sexual contact whatsoever it be because this man have decide to become an ascetic ie in Hinduism a person who give up the pleasure of the world to gain inner enlightenment now his wanting to do this be all well and good if he be not already marry and have obligation for his wife however be marry this be an incredibly selfish act and like his brother he assume his wife have no sexual feeling nor do he seem to care the close he would allow she to he sexually be to sleep next to he as have she next to he help teach himself to overcome the desire of the flesh this must have bring nothing but frustration to herbr br So you have get two neglected and normal woman live in the same household who long for emotional connection as well as an outlet for their sexual need eventually these need bring these sister in law together at first just emotionally but later sexually as well the movie be brilliant how it get I to look at and understand how in some case homosexuality be inevitable and even healthy compare to a life of emotional desolationbr br late in the film when the intensity of their sexual relationship be discover it lead to a not totally unexpected reaction from Radha s enlighten husband a man who seek religious insight and peace yet be so wrap up in himself that true insight and growth be impossiblebr br this be a very challenging and adult film while there be very little nudity the subject matter be very adult and this be not a film to show your kid very disturbing indeed be one minor character who masturbate in front of an old paralyzed lady as I say this be not a film to let your kid watch however for a mature audience this be an excellent and highly erotic film that will get you to thinkbr br The film feature good act complex character excellent writing lovely mood music and a slow pace that might annoy some but which I find rewarding the only serious negative I can not blame on the movie itself but on the idiot who release this on videotape this be because although the movie be in English the accent be quite strong at time and it be not always easy to understand what be be say but and this be the bad part there be no closed or open caption include they be a must for western audience if you do watch this film see if you can find it on dvd or hopefully a new release on video will have captioning mine sure didntbr br By the way director Deepa Mehta a popular female director have make several other wonderful film such as EARTH and BOLLYWOOD Hollywood a consistent theme in her film be the conflict between traditional indian culture and expectation and Westernism with a strong emphasis on female character not surprisingly this West thinking lady make her home in Canada and be divorce a truly unusual woman to say the least for a similar film that explore traditional culture meet western culture try another canadian gem EAT DRINK MAN WOMAN

overall a well do movie there be the part that make I wince and there be the part that I throw my hand up at but I come away with something more than I go in withbr br i think the movie suffer from some serious excess ambition without spoil it let I say that the obvious reference to the trial by fire in Ramayana be way beyond what this movie stand for the Ramayana be an epic not a 200 page book that put down woman in India the movie be about two girl marry into a very distinctive indian family while the basic tenet of the unwritten law of the family tradition seem to be that of conservative India let I assure my reader that I having live in Delhi for 12 year find entire part that just do not ring those bell I mean some thing and some action be very true but some other stuff be just way off the mark especially todaybr br Delhi be complicated India be complicated the director try to simplify both and fail pretty miserably at thatbr br why in English can you imagine a movie about American Indians in English or the French speak in English seriously jarring even the servant speak in fluent accented English albeit with a hint of colloquialism in the language for believabilitybr br But the chemistry between the lead be palpable if you like it hot this be a movie for you I think that be the big saving grace the development of a true real life love storybr br if this film be about Radha and Sita then it would have get full mark from I and in be about they it could have make a subtle statement but this movie go out there to say this be what India be and this be what indian society be like and in that respect it succeed as much as it fail just take everything you see with a pinch of salt the dark secret of India be not be reveal just two girl be fall in love just like it happen everywhere else

this be a great film in every sense of the word it tackle the subject of tribadism in a society that be quite intolerant of any deviation from the norm it criticise a great many indian custom that many find oppressive such as the arranging of marriage by other the importance of status and face religious hypocrisy sexism the valuation of woman in term of their baby make capacity the bind concept of duty and so on at the heart of the film be a touching love story that go beyond such limitation of the society which the two protagonist find themselves the film be well act and genuine completely believable from begin to end unlike most Bollywood flick the main fault of the film as I see it be first that the two lover seem draw to one another not necessarily by a natural affinity for each other as much as the fact that they be stick in dead end marriage with no passion and no reward this may play a part in the sexual awakening of the character but most people stick in the same situation will not turn homosexual it seem clear from the beginning of the film that the two character be quite heterosexual when Radha do her scene at the end of the movie with Aashok she make it quite clear that without desire she be dead and the implication be that if he have desire so he could have fulfil she quite completely and also when Sita seem very disappointed when her husband seem to not like she such situation do not turn people into homosexual they may seek comfort in other in the same position but inthe film it be not at all make clear that they be lesbian from the beginning quite the opposite some people be bisexual it be true but most tend to be either hetero or homosexual in the case of the lady in the film both have insensitive jerk for husband if this have not be the case would they have naturally find the need to express their desire in a relationship that they may have otherwise not have consider the film ignore this the other fault be the naming of the character the name Sita and Radha seem contrive deliberately to shock and outrage imagine a film in America depict a gay relationship between a man name Jesus and another name Paul by use name associate with various Hindoo scripture the film be strong enough to stand on its own and need no such device in my opinion at any rate the fault do not take much away from the power of the movie it be indeed a very touching and powerful story the image and character will stay with you a long time after you leave the theatre

this be my first Deepa Mehta film I see the film on tv in its Hindi version with its Sita character present as Nita I also note that it be Radha who undergo the allegorical trial by fire in the film and not Nita Sita yet what I love about the film be its screenplay by Ms Mehta not her direction the character big and small be well develop and seem quixotic towards the end somewhat like the end of Mazursky s an Unmarried Woman they be brave woman surround by cardboard man and one cardboard man Ashok seem to come alive in the last shot we see of he carry his invalid mother Biji he seem to remain reluctant to challenge the heroic optimistic and propagandistic stance towards warfare that have be prevalent in previous year it be not until 1957 that director Mikhail Kalatozov and writer 1958 Cannes Film Festivalbr br The crane be fly be both an invigorate visual feast and an audacious humanistic portrayal of war unlike many Soviet war theme film of the time it be less constrain by the archetypal figure of the traditional war time hero and more concerned with the futility brutality and indeed the inevitability of conflict love as a cinematic concept be too often idealise as a notion that somehow conquer all and endure endless hardship and yet the reality be substantially less romantic in the film two lover Veronika Tatyana Samojlova and Boris Aleksey Batalov separate by the advent of the WWII widely know in the Soviet Union as the Great Patriotic War 1941 1945 pledge to marry after the war but tragedy deny the couple their wish drive to betrayal by the unending torment and uncertainty of waiting Veronika agree to we d Boris cousin Mark Aleksandr Shvorin a handsome but unworthy youth the film may conclude with the proud victory of the Soviets and a patriotic flag wave parade but the optimism of this sequence be overwhelmingly eclipse by the bittersweet tragedy of our young female protagonist who wander soullessly through the celebrating crowdsbr br Perhaps the most remarkable feature of the Cranes be fly be Sergei Urusevsky s inspired and dynamic hand hold cinematography which realistically and dizzily capture the chaos and confusion of war not necessarily in the hail of gunfire and the cry of die comrade in fact only one of the film s sequence join Boris on the Eastern Front but from the perspective of the family and friend who be leave behind in one particularly impressive oft cite long shot the camera follow Veronika as she frantically search for Boris in a crowd of depart recruit and their family the hand hold camera smoothly follow the girl off a bus jostle through the crowd alongside her capture momentary snippet of love one say farewell to their son and husband before unexpectedly crane above the crowd as Veronika disappear into the dust of a pass squadron of army tank a breathtaking movement that offer scope and urgency to the dramatic episode Urusevsky first acquire his filming experience as a military cameraman during the war and obviously fall in love with the storytelle possibility of hand hold photography the camera he once declare can express what the actor be unable to portray his inner sensation the cameraman must act with the actor

68000 life since 1983 human right group have say that as a result of the war more than one million people have be displace homeless or live in camp the impact on child and family catch in the conflict be sensitively dramatize by acclaimed Tamil director Mani Ratnam in his 2002 film a Peck on the Cheek winner of several award at the National Film Awards in India while the civil war be merely a backdrop for the story of a young girl s voyage of discovery the human cost of war be make quite clear and Ratnam give the fighting a universal context point the finger at global arm trafficker as the source of wrongdoingbr br beautifully photograph in Southern India by cinematographer Ravi K Chandran in a setting mirror the terrain of Sri Lanka the film tell a move story about an adopt 9 year old middle class family with two young brother after her natural parent Shyama Nandita Das and Dileepan JD Chakravarthi be force to flee when the fighting break out leave she in a Red Cross camp in a loving flashback we see Amudha s adoptive parent father Thiru Madhavan a prominent Tamil writer and mother Indra Simran a tv personality marry to facilitate their adoption of the darker skin little girlbr br Young Amudha have no idea that she be adopt until it be spring upon she abruptly on her ninth birthday accord to the parent prior agreement while she be play Thiru tell she almost in a matter of fact tone that you be not our daughter and the response be predictable Distraught she question who her father be what her mother s name be why she give she up and so forth but few answer be forthcoming amudha run away several time until her parent agree to go to Sri Lanka to help she find her true mother now a fighter for the Tamil separatist the family s immersion in the reality of the civil war lead to some traumatic moment and difficult decision handle mostly with skill by Ratnam though a sequence where the family be catch in a crossfire feel amateurishbr br a Peck on the Cheek be of course a bollywood style film and that mean ton of music and melodrama the melodrama do not get in the way because of the strong performance by the lead actor however I find the musical dramatization of song by A R Rahman counter to the mood of the film with their slick high production technique and fast pace music video style editing yet the compelling nature of the story and the honesty in which it be tell transcend the film s limitation Tamil cinema have be criticize by many even within the country as be too clichd and commercial yet a Peck on the Cheek be both a film of entertainment and one that tackle serious issue that it successfully straddle the line between art and commerce be not a rejection but a tribute

sadness and nostalgia permeate late Chrysanthemums a 1954 film by japanese auteur Mikio Naruse now undergo a retrospective of his long unavailable film thank to James Quandt of Cinematheque Ontario and the Japan Foundation base on three story by Fumiko Hayashi Late Chrysanthemums tell the story of four retire geisha now middle aged whose life have become full of disappointment and regret performance be uniformly outstanding particularly that of Haruko Sugimura who star in film by Ozu s Late Spring float weed and Tokyo Story among other sugimura portray Kin a former Geisha who have no child and live only with her young maid who be unable to speakbr br She have become cynical about man and have turn her attention to money particularly real estate speculation and loan money to her friend Nobu Sadako Sawamura Tamae Chikako Hosokawa and Tomi Yuko Mochizuki all former geisha Kin s friend live in meager circumstance and complain about how Kin have become greedy and Tomi spend considerable time gambling to try and make end meet both Tomi and Tamae be in the process of lose their child Tamae s son be leave to work in the coalmine in Hokkaido and Tomi s daughter have decide to accept a marriage proposal from an old man both resist the change in their circumstance but come to accept it as inevitablebr br Two male friend visit Kin Seki a former lover with whom she once contemplate double suicide and tabe Ken Uehara another lover who she look forward to see again after many year her mood be upbeat but soon turn to resentment when she discover that the two man be only interested in borrow money naruse cut between two extended sequence seamlessly as Kin confront Tabe and Tomi and Tamae console each other over the loss of their child the dialogue be extremely natural and the character be woman of strength who though their future do not seem bright refuse to see themselves merely as victim Late Chrysanthemums have the simplicity humor and stoic acceptance of life prominent in the film of Ozu and be a bittersweet reminder of the slow passing of time and the comfort that memory and companionship can bring along the way
